{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2891ca18-3707-44dc-b78a-d9602c84ad1d","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 5. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or use `perfcollect`/`dotnet-counters` as alternatives.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd835001-75e6-42ed-bed2-c93d089aa2b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":400},"id":"cb766a9b-a636-40d4-a3d6-973199e9ae93","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:49:24.450Z","parentId":"abdbfe03-387f-49f1-91bf-0faf68f999e7"}
